It was my original intention to make Finn the MC, but basically every dystopic novel stars the Winston Smith-type cynic who understands the evil of the regime. That just wasn't interesting to me. That said, I still want him there as a foil, and he has his own journey which I've dedicated much of the story too. You need him as a contrast to the MC

Miles' core flaw is that he begins weak (as most people raised in a dystopia designed to make you submissive would). His journey is fundamentally a coming of age, and I think this speaks to the current zeitgeist. There is a war to emasculate men everywhere, so while we'd all like to self-insert as Finn, the truth is that most of us are turning out like Miles. The story's core question is, "How do you become strong if you are that person?"

At least, these are the thoughts that inspired me and the choice to write Miles as the MC. Maybe I sound pretentious as hell rn but I promise Miles becomes less insufferable past ch. 3, even if you'll probably like Finn a lot more.
